          "title": "Blood on the extremities, oil over the blood — consecration of the whole person",
          "body": "The central ceremony of the eighth day (vv. 14-18) is the chapter's most precise and theologically freighted gesture. The priest takes blood from the guilt offering and applies it to three specific points: the lobe of the right ear, the thumb of the right hand, the big toe of the right foot. Then he pours oil into his left palm, sprinkles it seven times before the Lord, and applies the remaining oil over the same three points — over the blood — then pours the rest over the person's head. The three body-points are not random. They trace the axis of a person's engagement with the world: the ear that hears and receives, the hand that works and acts, the foot that walks and directs the body's path. Blood first — the atonement that covers; oil second — the consecration that claims. This is identical to the ordination rite for Aaron and his sons in Leviticus 8:23-24. The restored leper receives the same bodily consecration as the high priest. The implication is staggering: full restoration to the covenant community is not second-class membership. The cleansed person is re-consecrated to God from ear to toe, now belonging entirely to Yahweh's service."
