          "body": "The closing torah-summary (vv. 54-57) functions as a colophon not only for chapter 14 but for the entire chapters 13-14 unit. It names every subject covered: infectious skin disease, scaly outbreak, mildew in clothing or house, swelling, scab, bright spot. The stated purpose — \"to teach when they are unclean and when they are clean\" — reveals that these laws are pedagogical at their core. They teach Israel to think in categories of clean and unclean, holy and common, excluded and restored. Canonically, Leviticus 14 stands behind the New Testament's account of Jesus cleansing lepers (Matt. 8:1-4; Luke 17:14), where Jesus explicitly tells the cleansed person to show himself to the priest and offer what Moses commanded. Jesus does not abolish the Leviticus 14 framework; He claims to fulfill it. Where the Levitical priest diagnoses and mediates from a distance, Jesus touches the unclean directly (Matt. 8:3), crossing the boundary the law required the priest to respect — and the impurity moves not from the leper to Jesus but the cleanness moves from Jesus to the leper. The chapter's entire typological grammar finds its antitype in the one who went outside the camp (Heb. 13:12-13) to bring the excluded back into the presence of God."
